WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.300 --> 00:00:02.300
Hey there future web developers.

2
00:00:02.700 --> 00:00:08.720
Did you know JavaScript has several ways to display data? Whether you're updating a web page or testing code?

3
00:00:09.320 --> 00:00:15.340
JavaScript's got you covered. Let's break it down into four simple methods quick and easy just like we like it.

4
00:00:17.440 --> 00:00:20.080
First up using inner HTML.

5
00:00:20.680 --> 00:00:22.840
This is like filling in a shape or form.

6
00:00:23.640 --> 00:00:27.200
JavaScript finds an existing element by its ID and updates the content.

7
00:00:27.640 --> 00:00:31.300
Here's how it works.

8
00:00:31.300 --> 00:00:35.700
This code grabs the p-tag with the ID demo and changes its content to...

9
00:00:36.380 --> 00:00:38.020
You guessed it.

10
00:00:38.020 --> 00:00:39.700
Hello world!

11
00:00:39.700 --> 00:00:42.300
Super handy for updating content dynamically.

12
00:00:43.540 --> 00:00:45.540
Next we have document write.

13
00:00:46.060 --> 00:00:51.420
It's like the loudspeaker of JavaScript. It outputs directly into the HTML document.

14
00:00:51.900 --> 00:00:59.920
But watch out. If you use document write after the page has loaded it wipes out everything on your page.

15
00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:03.150
See this example.

16
00:01:03.150 --> 00:01:05.510
Here we run the code when the user clicks the button.

17
00:01:06.030 --> 00:01:08.550
So after the page has finished loading.

18
00:01:09.020 --> 00:01:11.500
Oops, it replaces our entire page.

19
00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:15.280
So great for quick testing but not for production.

20
00:01:16.460 --> 00:01:18.460
Want to grab someone's attention?

21
00:01:18.460 --> 00:01:23.500
Use an alert box with window alert or just alert since the window part is optional.

22
00:01:23.940 --> 00:01:33.250
This pops up a box with the result. Great for quick notifications, but don't overuse it unless you like annoying your users.

23
00:01:35.880 --> 00:01:38.200
And finally the secret weapon for debugging.

24
00:01:38.600 --> 00:01:40.200
Console Log.

25
00:01:40.560 --> 00:01:42.560
Think of it like a journal for your code.

26
00:01:42.760 --> 00:01:45.400
It logs messages straight to the browser console.

27
00:01:47.370 --> 00:01:51.330
Use this to test your code behind the scenes without interrupting the user experience.

28
00:01:51.490 --> 00:01:55.020
It's a developer's best friend.

29
00:01:55.340 --> 00:01:58.780
When testing console methods you need to have the console view visible.

30
00:01:58.980 --> 00:02:01.620
This is usually opened by pressing F12.

31
00:02:04.200 --> 00:02:05.360
One last trick.

32
00:02:05.840 --> 00:02:11.880
While JavaScript doesn't have a direct send to printer function you can use window print to print the current page.

33
00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:15.880
Easy peasy, just one button click and voila.

34
00:02:16.320 --> 00:02:18.520
Old timey paper printed content.

35
00:02:19.490 --> 00:02:20.690
So there you have it.

36
00:02:20.930 --> 00:02:24.610
Four ways to display data in JavaScript plus a bonus printing tip.

37
00:02:24.890 --> 00:02:28.050
Try them out and see which one works best for your projects.

38
